{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8775111c-338a-4a08-a65b-a05764362c0b","content":"The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package:\n\n1. **Install it:** `dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions`\n2. **Inject `IFileSystem`** instead of calling static `File`/`Directory` methods:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyService\n{\n    private readonly IFileSystem _fs;\n\n    public MyService(IFileSystem fs) => _fs = fs;\n\n    public void Save(string path, string content)\n        => _fs.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n}\n```\n\n3. **In production:** register `new FileSystem()`.\n4. **In tests:** use `MockFileSystem` from `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`:\n\n```csharp\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nsvc.Save(\"/tmp/test.txt\", \"hello\");\nAssert.Equal(\"hello\", fs.File.ReadAllText(\"/tmp/test.txt\"));\n```\n\nThis covers `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`, and virtually every other `System.IO` API — no custom wrapper needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ef1911f6-eb89-4575-a1c2-6807f13a98b5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in .NET. This is a design/architecture question about dependency injection and abstraction of file system calls. Let me give a concise, practical answer.\n\nThe standard approach is to use `System.IO.Abstractions` — a well-known NuGet package that provides an `IFileSystem` interface wrapping all `System.IO` static calls. This lets you inject a mock/fake file system in tests.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase-specific task. I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"4813:1B7094:624EBEA:6A43D2E:69FBF251"},"id":"6c6e3375-122f-4b40-bea5-ac1f1d25362c","timestamp":"2026-05-07T02:00:58.261Z","parentId":"4f84034b-69f7-4d7c-bd8d-72d6ecc352b4"}
